'VidBuff' is just a region of memory into which you can write characters and Character strings with ordinary assembly language instructions. 
However, nothing will appear on your monitor until you send the buffer to the Linux console. 

This is easy enough. 
The procedure 'Show' makes a single call to the 'sys_write' kernel service via 'INT 80h', and sends the entire buffer to the console at once. 
The EOL characters embedded in the buffer every 'COLS' bytes are treated as EOL character always are by the console, and force a new line to begin immediately after each EOL. 
Becuase all the lines are the same length, sending 'VidBuff' to the console creates a rectanglar region of text that will display correctly on any terminal window that is at leaast 'COLS' by 'ROWS' in size. 

Whats important is that your prgrams call 'Show' whenever you want a screen update. 
This can be done as often as you want, whenever you want. 
On modern Linux PCs, the update happens so quickly as to appear instantaneous. 
There's no reason you shouldn't call 'Show' after each write to 'VidBuff'
